					<description><![CDATA[Note: The draft of this article had been staring back at me since April 2022. I&#8217;m only now getting around to publishing it. Consistent, timely and regular publishing is a natural skill of mine. Have you ever walked at night on a street that’s lit with street lights? As you pass the lamp post, you [&#8230;]]]></description>
										<content:encoded><![CDATA[
<p><em>Note: The draft of this article had been staring back at me since April 2022. I&#8217;m only now getting around to publishing it. Consistent, timely and regular publishing is a natural skill of mine.</em></p>



<p>Have you ever walked at night on a street that’s lit with street lights? As you pass the lamp post, you start to see a small shadow in front of you. Slowly, as you walk further, the shadow grows, and it keeps growing until it fades to the point where you can’t see it, the next lamp post’s illumination overpowers it or both.</p>



<p>I had this question pop in my mind about the rate at which such a shadow grows, and if is a constant speed or somehow accelerating as the person goes further and further away from the pole. To find it for myself, I spent some time figuring it out today; a lazy rainy Sunday afternoon.</p>



<p>Assuming that</p>



<ul class="wp-block-list">
<li>A person 1.8m tall</li>



<li>Walks at 2m/s</li>



<li>Past a lamppost 9m tall</li>
</ul>



<p>We&#8217;re asking, </p>



<ol class="wp-block-list">
<li>How fast is the head of the shadow moving away from the lamppost and </li>



<li>How fast is the head of the shadow moving away from the person</li>
</ol>



<p>Let&#8217;s draw some figures to better visualize the question.</p>



<figure class="wp-block-image size-full"><img fetchpriority="high" decoding="async" width="2560" height="2560" src="http://nagekar.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/08/visualize-scaled.jpg" alt="" class="wp-image-1969" srcset="https://nagekar.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/08/visualize-scaled.jpg 2560w, https://nagekar.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/08/visualize-300x300.jpg 300w, https://nagekar.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/08/visualize-250x250.jpg 250w" sizes="(max-width: 2560px) 100vw, 2560px" /></figure>



<p>To solve this problem, the first piece of information that we note is that the top of the pole, the bottom of the pole and the head of the shadow form a right angled triangle.</p>



<p>The top of the person&#8217;s head, their feet and the head of the shadow also form a right angled triangle.</p>



<p>Since we drew a line from the lamp to the person&#8217;s head extending all the way to the head of the shadow, the angles thus formed at the lamp and the person (θ) are the same. We conclude here that the smaller triangle is <em>similar</em> to the larger triangle.</p>



<p>Using the property of <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Similarity_(geometry)#Similar_triangles">similar triangles</a>, we get an equation of x in terms of y.</p>



<figure class="wp-block-image size-full"><img decoding="async" width="2560" height="864" src="http://nagekar.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/08/similartrianges-scaled.jpg" alt="" class="wp-image-1972" srcset="https://nagekar.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/08/similartrianges-scaled.jpg 2560w, https://nagekar.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/08/similartrianges-300x101.jpg 300w, https://nagekar.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/08/similartrianges-250x84.jpg 250w, https://nagekar.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/08/similartrianges-768x259.jpg 768w, https://nagekar.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/08/similartrianges-1536x519.jpg 1536w, https://nagekar.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/08/similartrianges-2048x691.jpg 2048w" sizes="(max-width: 2560px) 100vw, 2560px" /></figure>



<p>or <code>x = 4y</code></p>



<p>Since we already know the rate of change of <code>x</code>, which is just the walking speed of the person, we can take derivative on both sides to get the rate of change of <code>y</code>.</p>



<figure class="wp-block-image size-full"><img decoding="async" width="2471" height="1634" src="http://nagekar.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/08/dybydt.jpg" alt="" class="wp-image-1970" srcset="https://nagekar.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/08/dybydt.jpg 2471w, https://nagekar.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/08/dybydt-300x198.jpg 300w, https://nagekar.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/08/dybydt-250x165.jpg 250w, https://nagekar.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/08/dybydt-768x508.jpg 768w, https://nagekar.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/08/dybydt-1536x1016.jpg 1536w, https://nagekar.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/08/dybydt-2048x1354.jpg 2048w" sizes="(max-width: 2471px) 100vw, 2471px" /></figure>



<p>So the shadow is growing at 0.5m/s relative to the walking person. Or, if we want to get rate at which the head of the shadow is moving away from the lamppost, we express <code>z</code> in terms of <code>y</code> and then apply derivative on both sides.</p>



<figure class="wp-block-image size-full"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" width="2560" height="1390" src="http://nagekar.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/08/dzbydt-scaled.jpg" alt="" class="wp-image-1971" srcset="https://nagekar.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/08/dzbydt-scaled.jpg 2560w, https://nagekar.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/08/dzbydt-300x163.jpg 300w, https://nagekar.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/08/dzbydt-250x136.jpg 250w, https://nagekar.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/08/dzbydt-768x417.jpg 768w, https://nagekar.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/08/dzbydt-1536x834.jpg 1536w, https://nagekar.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/08/dzbydt-2048x1112.jpg 2048w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 2560px) 100vw, 2560px" /></figure>



<p>2.5m/s away from the lamppost or 0.5m/s faster than the person walking, which it why it seems to grow in length away from us the further we go from the lamppost.</p>



<h2 class="wp-block-heading">In closing</h2>



<p>Hope you enjoyed reading this silly thought, and perhaps even learned something. Thank you for reading!</p>
]]></content:encoded>
					
		
		
